Certainly! Below, I'll provide the basic structure of a Vue component that consists of two parts as described. The first part includes menu entries with toggle buttons, and the second part displays the items toggled from the first menu.

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <div class="menu-entries">
      <div v-for="(item, index) in menuItems" :key="index">
        <span>{{ item.name }}</span>
        <button @click="toggleItem(index)">
          {{ item.isVisible ? 'Hide' : 'Show' }}
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="toggled-menu">
      <div v-for="(item, index) in toggledItems" :key="index">
        {{ item.name }}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  name: 'ToggleMenuComponent',

  data() {
    return {
      menuItems: [
        { name: 'Menu 1', isVisible: false },
        { name: 'Menu 2', isVisible: false },
        { name: 'Menu 3', isVisible: false },
        // Add more menu items here
      ],
    };
  },

  computed: {
    toggledItems() {
      return this.menuItems.filter(item => item.isVisible);
    },
  },

  methods: {
    toggleItem(index) {
      const item = this.menuItems[index];
      item.isVisible = !item.isVisible;
    },
  },
};
</script>

<style scoped>
/* Add your styles here */
.menu-entries {
  /* Menu entries styling */
}

.toggled-menu {
  /* Toggled menu styling */
}
</style>
```

In this component:

- `menuItems` is an array that keeps track of each menu item and its visibility state.
- The `toggleItem` method is used to toggle the visibility of a menu item.
- The `toggledItems` computed property returns the list of items that are currently set to visible.
- The first part of the template loops through `menuItems` and displays a button for each item that allows toggling visibility.
- The second part of the template loops through `toggledItems` and displays only the items that have their `isVisible` property set to `true`.
- Styling should be added according to your project's design specifications.

Remember that the above is a basic example. Depending on your specific needs, you may want to add more features, such as animations, better styling, or additional functionality. Remember to handle edge cases and make your component as reusable as possible.

