In this updated version:

- The `menuNames` array stores a list of menu names.
- The `toggledMenus` array keeps track of the menus that have been toggled to be shown.
- When a button is clicked, the `toggleMenu` method is called to add or remove the menu from the `toggledMenus` array.
- The lists of menus and toggled menus are rendered in the template using `v-for`.

Understood. Here's the code modified to support local storage for toggled menu values:

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <div class="menu-entries">
      <div v-for="menu in menuNames" :key="menu">
        <span>{{ menu }}</span>
        <button @click="toggleMenu(menu)">
          {{ isMenuToggled(menu) ? 'Hide' : 'Show' }}
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="toggled-menu">
      <div v-for="menu in toggledMenus" :key="menu">
        {{ menu }}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  name: "ToggleMenuComponent",

  data() {
    return {
      menuNames: ["Home", "Profile", "Settings"],
      toggledMenus: JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("toggledMenus")) || []
    };
  },

  methods: {
    toggleMenu(menuName) {
      const index = this.toggledMenus.indexOf(menuName);
      if (index > -1) {
        this.toggledMenus.splice(index, 1);
      } else {
        this.toggledMenus.push(menuName);
      }
      this.updateLocalStorage();
    },
    updateLocalStorage() {
      localStorage.setItem("toggledMenus", JSON.stringify(this.toggledMenus));
    },
    isMenuToggled(menuName) {
      return this.toggledMenus.includes(menuName);
    }
  },

  watch: {
    toggledMenus: {
      handler(toggledMenus) {
        localStorage.setItem("toggledMenus", JSON.stringify(toggledMenus));
      },
      deep: true
    }
  }
};
</script>

<style scoped>
.menu-entries div {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.menu-entries span {
  margin-right: 10px;
}

.toggled-menu div {
  margin-top: 10px;
}
</style>
```

This code includes the following updates:

- The `toggledMenus` data property is initialized from `localStorage` if available, otherwise, it starts as an empty array.
- The `toggleMenu` method toggles the selected menu and calls `updateLocalStorage` to update the `localStorage`.
- A separate method `updateLocalStorage` is created for updating `localStorage`.
- A computed property `isMenuToggled` determines if the menu name is present in the `toggledMenus` array for setting the button text.
- A watcher for `toggledMenus` is added to automatically update `localStorage` when the `toggledMenus` data property changes. This ensures persistence even if the component updates the list outside of `toggleMenu` method.

To integrate Vue Router with menu links, you'll need to have Vue Router installed and configured in your Vue application. Assuming you have Vue Router set up and with some routes defined, I'll provide you with an example of how you can modify your component to include router links for each menu item. We'll make each menu item correspond to a route.

Firstly, ensure you have Vue Router installed:
```bash
npm install vue-router
```

Then, set up your routes in your main JavaScript file (e.g., `main.js` or `router.js`):

```javascript
import Vue from 'vue';
import VueRouter from 'vue-router';
import HomeComponent from './components/HomeComponent';
import ProfileComponent from './components/ProfileComponent';
import SettingsComponent from './components/SettingsComponent';

Vue.use(VueRouter);

const routes = [
  { path: '/home', component: HomeComponent, name: 'Home' },
  { path: '/profile', component: ProfileComponent, name: 'Profile' },
  { path: '/settings', component: SettingsComponent, name: 'Settings' }
  // Add other routes here
];

const router = new VueRouter({
  mode: 'history',
  routes
});

export default router;
```

Now, in your component, you'd integrate router links like this:

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <div class="menu-entries">
      <div v-for="route in $router.options.routes" :key="route.name">
        <router-link :to="route.path">{{ route.name }}</router-link>
        <button @click="toggleMenu(route.name)">
          {{ isMenuToggled(route.name) ? 'Hide' : 'Show' }}
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="toggled-menu">
      <div v-for="menu in toggledMenus" :key="menu">
        {{ menu }}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  name: "ToggleMenuComponent",

  data() {
    return {
      toggledMenus: JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("toggledMenus")) || []
    };
  },

  methods: {
    toggleMenu(menuName) {
      const index = this.toggledMenus.indexOf(menuName);
      if (index > -1) {
        this.toggledMenus.splice(index, 1);
      } else {
        this.toggledMenus.push(menuName);
      }
      this.updateLocalStorage();
    },
    updateLocalStorage() {
      localStorage.setItem("toggledMenus", JSON.stringify(this.toggledMenus));
    },
    isMenuToggled(menuName) {
      return this.toggledMenus.includes(menuName);
    }
  },

  watch: {
    toggledMenus(newVal) {
      localStorage.setItem("toggledMenus", JSON.stringify(newVal));
    }
  }
};
</script>

<style scoped>
.menu-entries div {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.menu-entries span {
  margin-right: 10px;
}

.router-link-active {
  font-weight: bold;
}

.toggled-menu div {
  margin-top: 10px;
}
</style>
```

In this modified component:

- Instead of listing the menu names manually, we loop over `$router.options.routes` to generate router links for each route.
- `router-link` becomes the means of navigating to the different routes.
- The `toggleMenu` method and localStorage interaction remains similar, but now tied to the route names.

This code assumes that your Vue Router is in history mode and that you're using named routes. Please adjust the code to fit the actual setup of your routes and router configuration.
